1 Bringing in the Data and Basic Plotting

For this exercise, I decided to use Swaziland (now called Eswatini). I downloaded the geometry data as outlined in the instructions and brought in the data using the read_sf() function from the sf library.

The first plot that I made simply includes the international boundary and first level administrative boundaries, using the geom_sf() and goem_sf_text() functions from ggplot.

This is a nice plot, but is a bit basic on its own. To convey more information, I added the second level administrative boundaries.

Bringing in second level administrative boundaries clutters up the plot a bit, but its still legible. To ensure that smaller features were less prominent, I decreased the size argument and moved along a greyscale for color in the geom_sf_text() and geom_sf() functions. This makes the plot much more readable.

2 Stretch Goals

In this section, I include the results from a few of the stretch goals in the first part of this exercise (titled Individual Stretch Goal 2 and Individual Stretch Goal 3).

2.1 Looking at the Most Populous Region

After a little searching, I learned that Eswatini is divided into four regions (Hhohho, Lubombo, Manzini, and Shiselweni) and each region is further divided into many tinkhundla (their second level of administrative subdivision). For instance, the region Hhohho is split into the tinkhundla Hhukwini, Lobamba, Madlangempisi, Mayiwane, Mbabane East, Mbabane West, Mhlangatane, Motjane, Mphalaleni, Ndzingeni, Nkhaba, Ntfonjeni, Piggs Peak, and Timpisini.

The most populous region in Eswatini is Manzini, which is comprised of 16 tinkhundla. Heres a plot of Manzini on its own.

2.2 Arranging Plots

Finally, I put a few plots together on the same axes. The idea here was to identify a couple of different areas on the country map and then to zoom in on those areas of interest.

This is really a nice plot. I especially had fun fiddling with the different axis elements (i.e., panel.border, panel.background, axis.ticks, etc.) to make the plot more clear. The one issue is that the labels in the Manzini plot overlap, making it a little hard to read.
